"""
era_three_reversals.py -- Christ's Triple Victory (Chapters 7-8)

Three rebellions, three reversals. Each rebellion has a specific,
corresponding act of Christ that undoes it:

1. Eden (Nachash/Satan) --> Cross (Col 2:15): Christ disarms the
   rulers and authorities, making a public spectacle of them.
   The Roman triumphal procession imagery -- defeated enemies
   paraded behind the victor.

2. Hermon (Watchers) --> Proclamation to imprisoned spirits
   (1 Pet 3:19): kerysso, not euangelizo. This is not a gospel
   invitation but a victory declaration. Christ descends to the
   prison of the Watchers and announces that their rebellion has
   been defeated.

3. Babel (territorial princes) --> Pentecost (Acts 2): The reversal
   of Babel's linguistic scattering. The verb diamerizo appears in
   both Acts 2:3 ('divided tongues of fire') and LXX Deut 32:8
   ('when he divided mankind'). God is reclaiming the nations.
"""

